age/529797731950592-1503325030452_Q64/Raubal-Martin.jpg\" class=\"lite-image\" alt=\"Raubal Martin\"/></picture></span><span class=\"nova-legacy-v-person-inline-item__fullname\">Raubal Martin</span></span></a></li></ul></div><div class=\"nova-legacy-v-publication-item__stack-item\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-e-text nova-legacy-e-text--size-m nova-legacy-e-text--family-sans-serif nova-legacy-e-text--spacing-none nova-legacy-e-text--color-inherit nova-legacy-e-text--clamp-3 nova-legacy-v-publication-item__description\"><span class=\"js-target-abstract-61a68d3836d94 lite-page-hidden\">Abstract Multi-criteria decision analysis enhances ,location-based queries to a ,more ,personalized level. However, while there are assumptions on how such analysis supports people in their decision-making during the performance of spatio-temporal tasks, these assumptions have only been based on models,so far. This paper focuses on the,benefits and drawbacks,of a personalized mobile location-based decision service by evaluating ,the results of a human subject test. The test described three different user scenarios and was performed ,using a Smartphone. The prototype application featured multi-criteria decision support for the task of finding suitable hotels in the city of M\u00fcnster, Germany.</span></div></div></div></div><footer class=\"nova-legacy-v-publication-item__footer\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-v-publication-item__footer-actions\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-o-pack nova-legacy-o-pack--gutter-m nova-legacy-o-pack--width-auto nova-legacy-o-pack--vertical-align-middle\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-o-pack__item nova-legacy-v-publication-item__footer-button-group\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-c-button-group nova-legacy-c-button-group--gutter-m nova-legacy-c-button-group--orientation-horizontal nova-legacy-c-button-group--width-auto nova-legacy-v-publication-item__actions\"><div class=\"nova-legacy-c-button-group__item\"><a class=\"nova-legacy-c-button nova-legacy-c-button--align-center nova-leg